@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@prev "Main"
  @{b}Introduction@{ub}
  ViewerPrefs is a new preferences editor that lets you select what
  viewers Workbench should use for files of certain types, when you click
  on their Workbench icons.
  To run this program you need to have the program "IDer" (util/wb/ider.lha)
  in your c: dir, and then change the default tool of all your icons to
  it.
    This way no hacks of any sort are necessary, and you can remove all
  such hacks as "ToolAlias" is MCP, as you won't need them anymore.
    All settings to do with default tools will be handled by a single
  preferences editor: "Viewers".
    Eg. Whenever you download any new viewer, like a new 24-bit fast ppc
  jpeg viewer, all you have to do is drop it's icon on the preferences editor
  and all the JPEGs on your system will be now shown with the new program.
    Also, you will be able to copy a project icon from one file to another
  with the CLI or Workbench or whatever and double-clicking on the icon it
  will automatically load the right viewer for it's new type of file.  You
  can just copy it without changing anything else.
    All these great options are actually properties of the little (fast)
  assembler program IDer, and ViewerPrefs is just a nice way of letting
  you change all these options with a new preferences editor.

  The inspiration for ViewerPrefs was "CUCDPrefs"  The Amiga Magazine Cover CD
  Preferences Editor, which inspired me to write an editor which, using IDer,
  could (if you wanted to) be used in a general sense as sort of "Viewers"
  system preferences editor.
@next "Distribution"
@endnode

@node "Distribution" "Distribution"
@prev "Introduction"
  @{b}Distribution@{ub}
  ViewerPrefs is Freeware.  I'm sure you've got better things to spend your
  cash on, like PPC boards!
  This package may be distributed via whatever means you want, provided
  the archive remains intact and none of the files in it are modified.

  @{b}Disclaimer@{ub}
  By using this product, you accept the full responsibility for any damage
  or loss that might occur through its use.  I (Ian Campbell) can not be
  held responsible.
@next "Requirements"
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "System Requirements"
@prev "Distribution"
  @{b}System Requirements@{ub}
    - Kickstart 3.0 or higher
    - 68020 CPU or higher
    - MUI 3.8 or higher (aminet: util/libs/mui38usr.lha)
      (It may work on an earlier MUI, but at least 2.0 as it uses
      custom classes)
    - IDer 1.06 (aminet: util/wb/ider.lha)
 
    It was programmed on an A1200 3.1 and MUI Demo 3.8 so it should at
    least work with that.
@next "Features"
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"
@prev "Requirements"
  @{b}Features@{ub}

    - Drag & Drop a datatype icon to automatically create a new entry.
    - 'Expert Mode' allows editing of every gritty detail of config file
    - 'Easy Mode' for everyday usage.
    - Partial loading of corrupt config files
    - Allows a "Reset to Defaults" config file
    - Sorting of config files.
    - MUI Interface, so customisable to your "unique" idea of style.
      (whatever that may be) <gulp!>
    - All buttons/menus etc. work like all your other prefs editors, so you
      can throw this guide away now!
    - Fully Localised English, German, Italian and Serbian languages
    - English & Italian Docs
    - Context sensitive help and bubble help.
@next "Installation"
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@prev "Features"
  @{b}Installation@{ub}
  Use the installer script or just drag the Viewers icon anywhere and (optionally)
  set the @{"HELPFILE" link "Configuration" 0} tooltype to get online help
  and the @{"DEFFILE" link "Configuration" 0} tooltype to get the Reset to Defaults option
  and copy any language catalogs you want to Locale:Catalogs/<Language>.

  A good fast program for changing default tools to IDer is called DEFT-II. (aminet)
@next "Configuration"
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"
@prev "Installation"
  ViewerPrefs is currently only run from the Workbench and can be configured
  through the following (all optional) tooltypes.

  @{b}SAVENAME@{ub}   - This is the name/path to save the config file to
               when you click on 'Save'.
               Default: "envarc:IDer.prefs"
 
  @{b}USENAME@{ub}    - This is the name/path to save the config file to
               when you click on 'Use'.
               Default: "env:IDer.prefs"

  @{b}DEFNAME@{ub}    - This is the name/path to load the config file from
               when you chose the "Reset To Defaults" menu item.
               The default is just a config file I made in the directory,
               but this could be anything. eg. if you were using
               IDer + ViewerPrefs for your data laden CD-ROM and wanted the
               user to be able to modify the viewers for their own setup,
               this would be used to point to a config file on your CD that
               you know is good, just in case they screw it up.  Or you could
               grab the original file from the IDer archive, which is also
               quite good, but which I didn't want to redistribute without
               permission.
               Default: "progdir:def_IDer.prefs"

  @{b}HELPNAME@{ub}   - This is the name/path of the IDer guide file.  If
               you specify this then pressing help will load it.
               Default: "progdir:Docs/ViewerPrefs.guide"

  @{b}EXPERTMODE@{ub} - =(YES|NO) Start up in the 'Expert' aka. 'The Horrible
               Truth' mode.  Default is NO. (the 'Blissfully Ignorant-
               I know Nozink-turn off the X-Files-LaLaLaLa I can't hear you'
               Mode)

  @{b}CREATEICONS@{ub} - =(YES|NO) If for some sick reason you like to save
               lots of little config files everywhere with 'Save As' then
               this will help you to keep track of them.
               You never get icons with the 'Save' and 'Use' buttons.
               Default: YES (to be consistent with the system editors)
@next "EasyDisplay"
@endnode

@node "EasyDisplay" "The Easy Display"
@prev "Configuration"
  @{b}The Easy Display@{ub}
  This is pretty easy.

  @{b}The name above the listview@{ub} - shows the filename of the config file
  that was loaded at startup since it may have had to load the original file.
  This is not the name it will be saved as when you click on save.  This is
  always determined by the @{"SAVENAME" link "Configuration" 0} tooltype and it's default.
  If you want to see what the save name will be, pause the mouse pointer
  over save button for a few seconds.

  @{b}The Listview@{ub} - Errmm.. a listview.  Sorting?  I have not implemented a
  sort function here.  This is because the order of the file is important.  It is
  the order in which IDer searches for a match, so you should put your strongest
  and most common matches at the top, and not just sort it into alphabetical order,
  which, if you have some weak matches, could actually change the behaviour of
  IDer. Not good.
  You can however rearrange it yourself (manually, carefully) using the
  "Bubble Up" & "Bubble Down" arrows.

  @{b}The BubbleUp Arrow@{ub} - swaps the currently selected entry with the
  one above it. You can't bubble the default (last) entry up.

  @{b}The BubbleDown Arrow@{ub} - swaps the currently selected entry with the
  one below it. You can't bubble anything down below the default (last)
  entry.

  @{b}The Delete Button@{ub} - deletes the entry currently displayed. If you
  try to delete the last entry you will get a config file that just has a
  default option of Multiview.  How exciting.

  @{b}Dropping a tool@{ub} - anywhere but the slider will set the Action
  for this class to the filename you dropped.

  @{b}Dropping a Datatype Descriptor@{ub} on the slider automatically creates
  a new file entry, based on the file description contained in the Datatype.
  See: @{"Technical" link "Technical" 0}

  @{b}Save, Use, Test, Cancel@{ub} - Do what they always do.  In this case you
  can specify the save names the will be attached to these buttons.
  See: @{"Configuration" link "Configuration" 0} Remember that the Save button will always
  save to SAVENAME @{b}and@{ub} USENAME, (eg. env: as well as envarc:)
@next "ExpertDisplay"
@endnode

@node "Technical"
@prev "Easy Display"
  Dropping a Datatype icon on the slider and it will parse the datatype and
  create a new entry for you.  This is good as there are loads of these now.

    @{b}What the parser grabs:@{ub}
    The CLASS field: is constructed by concatenating dth_Name with
    dth_GroupID eg. GIF+Picture = GIF_Picture; 8SVX + Sound = 8SVX_Sound.

    @{b}The NAME field:@{ub} If the DTD contains a filename reg expn eg. #?.(jpg|jpeg)
    this will be placed in the name field.

    @{b}The OFFSET field:@{ub} If the DTD contains a file Mask this will be stored
    in the offset field with "0," prepended.  Also, it will be stored as
    an ASCII mask if all of the characters in the mask are printable
    (ctype.h/isprint()) or as a hex mask otherwise.

    @{b}The FLAGS=I subfield:@{ub} The value of this the datatypes CaseSensitive bit
    will also be used to set IDer's FLAGS=I bit. (To the opposite value.)

    @{b}The FLAGS=T subfield:@{ub} This flag is set if the datatype contains both
    a mask and a (non-#?) filetype description.  (So I assumed AND - the stricter
    the better)

    @{b}The ACTION field:@{ub} (futuristic :) If the datatype contains one or more
    DTTL (Datatype Tool) chunks and one of them has a type of '3' (= editor
    tool) then this program will be straight away placed in the Action field.
    Failing that it will try to insert the type 2 (= browser) tool there.
    I do not know of any datatypes which currently use this feature, even
    the excellent akdatatypes, which would be a perfect opportunity to
    advertise SuperView I would have thought!

    @{b}Datatypes with custom code identification hooks:@{ub}
    If the datatype uses a custom comparison hook to identify it's files
    (an example of this is the MacSnd datatype) then it will be rejected
    by ViewerPrefs (for obvious reasons).
@next "ExpertDisplay"
@endnode

@node "ExpertDisplay" "The Expert Display"
@prev "EasyDisplay"
  @{b}The Expert Display@{ub}
  This is pretty easy too really.

  If you've edited an IDer config file by hand before, it would be quicker
  to read @{"this" link "TextEdit" 0}.

  With the expert display you get an extra bit at the bottom which lets
  you edit the actual class definitions themselves.
  The top half also has some extra bits too, there is an insert button now
  as well as a delete button, and the Class Name text has changed to
  an input string.

  @{b}Insert@{ub} - Creates a new, blank entry for your manual editing.

  @{b}Stack:@{ub} - The stack size for the program in Action. Default is
           4096 bytes.

  @{b}Pri:@{ub}   - The Amiga multitasks you know :) This is the program's
           priority, from -127 to 128. Default is 0.

  @{b}No Filename Quote@{ub} - Tick this if your (old) program can't parse
                      filenames in quotes, otherwise IDer will put
                      quotes around the filename to allow spaces.

  @{b}Match: Cycle@{ub} - IDer has the 3 ways displayed to identify a file
                 (suffix, filename and character string somewhere in the
                 file.  How many of these must match before it is
                 satisfied and runs the tool?

  @{b}Name:@{ub} - This is an AmigaDOS regular expression liek the ones you
          see in the shell all the time. eg (mod.#?|#?.mod)

  @{b}Suffix:@{ub} - If you don't need the power of the name option, then you
            can just use this, eg. .GIF

  @{b}String:@{ub} - This is the most powerful option.  Did you know that most
            filetypes actually have some sort of identifier inside the
            file to say what it is.  If you know this you can enter
            it here.
            Use: <offset>, <value> for a magic number (and express it
            in hexadecimal notation eg. 16,DE..BE.. (.. is a wildcard)
            Use: <offset>, "string" if there's actually a printable
            string that's always in there that you know about.
            eg. Amigaguide documents always start with @database so you
            would put 0,@database.            (? is the wildcard here)
            This is the strongest match because it will work even they
            name the file to something else eg. a jpeg ending in .gif!
            This field is nearly always filled in when you drag and
            drop a datatype icon.

  @{b}Non Case-Sensitive@{ub} - If you're using a printable string match then
                      you should really set this.
                      With this set, @Database, @dataBase, and even
                      @DaTaBaSE (eg. for some try-hard software
                      pirate's .guide file :) would count too.

  Don't worry, you don't have to memorise all this... there's bubble help.
@next "Author"
@endnode

@node "TextEdit" "Expert Display"
@prev "ExpertDisplay"
  @{b}I was a text file editor...@{ub}
  All the String Gadget's names correspond exactly to their equivalent
  parameter names in the config file except:

   The "String"             contents which are put in as "OFFSET=".
   The "Non case sensitive" check activates the "I" flag.
   The "No Filename Quote"  check activates the "Q" flag.
   The "Match:"             cycle activates the "A" and "T" flags.
@next "Author"
@endnode

@node "Author" "Contacting the Author"
@prev "ExpertDisplay"
  @{b}Contact Info
  @{b}EMail:@{ub}
             icampbell@xtra.co.nz

  @{b}About me@{ub}
    I am a 23 year old programmer living in Wellington on the North Island of
    New Zealand, where wild animals roam free through the untouched
    mountains, the air is clean and fresh, and there are 100 year old trees
    everywhere. But, more importantly, Internet access is only $40(=13 GBP)
    a month for all you can eat, local telephone calls are free, and MTV Europe
    is a free-to-air TV Station :)))
    I also have a BSc in Computer Science from Victoria University of
    Wellington, where I learned C++, the language of IDer.

    I have been a dedicated Amigan since I sold my C64 in 1989 and brought
    an A500.  My current system is an A1200 Blizzard '030/50, 16+2 RAM, 6xCDROM,
    C=1942 Monitor and two 2.5" drives crammed in there - a 500Mb and a 60Mb.
    (Perhaps "the" average Amiga system these days or is '040 pretty much
    standard now?)

    ViewerPrefs was merely written to distract myself from the currently looming
    question "What should I do with my life?" as I have just returned from a year's
    working holiday in the UK and now I have to make some plans. (Doh! I hate it
    when that happens :)
    So anyway please send me plenty of bug reports/suggestions so I will have an
    excuse to keep procrastinating!
@next "Thanks"
@endnode

